      \field{extradatescope}{labelyear}
      \field{labeldatesource}{year}
      \field{labelnamesource}{author}
      \field{labeltitlesource}{title}
      \field{abstract}{In this book, we continue the investigations of global attractors and invariant sets for dynamical systems by means of Lyapunov functions and adapted metrics. The effectiveness of such approaches for the approximation and localization of attractors for different classes of dynamical systems was already shown in Abramovich et al. and in other works. In particular, Lyapunov functions and adapted metrics were constructed for global stability problems and the existence of homoclinic orbits in the Lorenz system using frequency-domain methods and reduction principles. In 1980, investigators of differential equations and general dynamical systems were greatly impressed by a paper about upper estimates of the Hausdorff dimension of flow and map invariant sets written by Douady and Oesterl{é}. The Douady--Oesterl{é} approach, the significance of which can be compared with that of Liouville's theorem, has been developed and modified in many papers for various types of dimension characteristics of attractors generated by dynamical systems: Ledrappier, Constantin et al., Smith, Eden et al., Chen, Hunt, and Boichenko and Leonov. After Ya. B. Pesin had worked out a general scheme of introducing metric dimension characteristics, this method made it possible to define from a unique point of view various types of outer measures and dimensions, such as the Hausdorff dimension, the fractal dimension, the information dimension as well as the topological and metric entropies. The Pesin scheme naturally led to the characterization of a class of Carath{é}odory measures, which are adapted to the specific character of attractors of autonomous differential equations, i.e., to the fact that these attractors consist wholly of trajectories. The neighborhoods of pieces of these trajectories form a covering of the attractor. It serves as the base for introducing the special outer Carath'{e}odory measures. A number of effective tools for estimating these measures were developed within the theory of differential equations in Euclidean space and well-known results by Borg, Hartman and Olech when analysing the orbital stability of solutions. The most important property, used in dimension theory, is the fact that the Carath'{e}odory measures are majorants for the associated Hausdorff measures.}
      \field{title}{Attractor dimension estimates for dynamical systems: theory and computation}
      \field{year}{2020}
      \true{nocite}
    \endentry
